snippet.textDisplay:
The title has a missing word: "Currently" or something along those lines. Of course this could be implied from context historically. Alternatively adding to the end of the title " (as of february 2020).
I see the current version of GPT2 was addressed, but could some even larger transformer (or a newer kind of deep neural net model) solve this to a human skill level? Seemingly not implausible. Given the kind of results seen from Open-AI's GPT2 where it could infer real world relations from having been only trained on text and (seemingly) internalizing semantic relations. An example of such semantic reference coherency (although picked from a set of options as a representative possible output) would be the generated news article of unicorns discovered by scientists to live in an isolated valley in the Andies , where based on prompted text it infered that the scientists would have latin-derived names and work at a university located in south america. It seems modern very large neural nets can embed non-textual semtantic context represented in the body of text they are trained on.
Another example of how much better DNNs have gotten at natural language is Google Translate. Just 2-3 years ago, and I can remember as recent as a bit over a year ago, translating a phrase through a pipe of 3-5 languages from different branches often gave totally nonsensical garbage. Even between pairs of languages that don't map very well onto each other grammatically or in choice of words would make text obviously translated by a machine (or human not fluent in those languages and with little context). Now recently, played around with this a bit again after having translated some very complex text with surprisingly good results, and the improvement is staggering.
10 years away to pass tests like the trophy in the suitcase or the cloth on the table is starting to seem like it might be a bit pessimistic. Especially when considering new tech like the Cerebras Wafer Scale Engine - a DNN optimized supercomputer taking up an entire silicon wafer which is un-cut, weighing in at 56x larger than the biggest GPU ever while being a single chip, accelerating training of large models by one to two orders of magnitude compared to typical GPU clusters.
